First of all, let me acknowledge: HEAD SHOTS CAN BE EXPENSIVE. So can hair appointments, while we’re on the subject...

But I have often chosen to get more affordable headshots more frequently, as opposed to spending a grand every few years. Neither approach is wrong and only you can make that financial decision for yourself and your career! For me, it started with my college pixie that I decided to grow out right before moving to LA. It changed a lot in a short period of time and I tried my best to keep up with it. That kinda got me more comfortable with (and inspired by) the idea of changing it up pretty often! Like, approximately once a year.

This has really worked for me. My look can go from completely lost in the crowd, basic girl to funky girl that sticks out with just a little hair and wardrobe shift. But I also want to mention something I’ve heard from a CD: if you have somewhat established relationships with casting offices (often getting called in by the same casting directors but not yet on a first name basis with them) changing up your headshots a lot can make it hard for them to keep track of you in a sea of submissions. And if you’re unsure, talk to your agent!

Quick question actors: are you getting less specific wardrobe notes recently? Things like “something that reflects your personal style” or “typical Gen Z” etc? I am! And while it’s fun to costume myself for these broad interpretations...sometimes I get overwhelmed and think I need to come up with something from scratch every time. 

Instead, I took an hour or so and shopped my closet to come up with a few go-to audition outfits that I love/that inspire me! If you’re also getting these kind of wardrobe notes in your audition tickets, I highly suggest it. Then you have more time to prep your sides instead of try on a million things! 🎬

💪 It’s time to redefine the notion of “work” for actors. No more condescending “are you working?” questions. No more “out of work” vs “working actor” labels. 

Modern actors are “workingggg” almost every day. If they’re not on set, they’re memorizing and taping auditions. If they’re not auditioning, they’re submitting their resumes and headshots and other materials to hopefully GET an audition. If they’re not yet submitting, they’re getting those materials ready. They’re booking headshot shoots, writing reel scenes for themselves and lining up help to film them, even formatting PDF resumes (which they also have to input, line by line, on the afore-mentioned casting sites 🙃) 

The list of “work” that actors are asked to do ✨for free...or even work they must ultimately PAY for ✨ before booking actual jobs is never-ending. But we do it because we adore it. 

So. If you’re doing anything to advance your career as an actor and making it a top priority, congratulations! You ARE a working actor. You are a legitimate, contributing member of your artistic community. I see you! Go get ‘em! 💪
🌈 Some call me the Jane Fonda of acting info reels...(please call me that) 🌈

Hey 👋🏻 Growing up in the thinness-obsessed 90’s gave me some pretty weird ideas as a kid. Every actress on TV looked like she was created in a futuristic lab to have very specific body dimensions... it was freaky! And they looked very little like any of the women in my world. Let alone me. I truly started to wonder if there was some physical inspection the magical gatekeepers put women through before every audition to make sure no normies accidentally made it onto TV. 

Unfortunately, I wasn’t too far off. Hollywood has a wildly sexist history of putting femme folk through a litany of screen tests, mandated diets and even surgical procedures to make them as “aspirational” as possible.

But things are slowly shifting. And every time we show up to this job as our authentic selves, pimples and all, I like to think we nudge the needle a little bit further. It’s not always easy, but I’m right there with you. Wear the tiny top! Visualize yourself as the “aspirational” romantic lead! Practice body positive/body neutral mantras if that’s helpful! You’re more than enough ❤️

🚗 You guys asked for more of these so here we go! In my last day in the life reel, I forgot to film anything about my commercial audition. So today I’m bringing you to a commercial callback…fingers crossed that (my pretend friends in the elevator and) I book it!

1. Have you heard about keeping a record/journal of each audition so you can keep track of which casting directors are calling you in the most? I think this concept came about when most auditions were done in person as a way of making note of who you met and what happened “in the room.” Audition journals can be helpful for tracking all sorts of things! But just know that, when you’re first starting out, you probably won’t see a pattern in terms of casting directors. 

This is bc many indie/small projects don’t even hire CD’s; they’re cast by the director or the producer…who are often the same person. Once you do get to the point of noticing casting directors auditioning you multiple times, a quick and easy way to double check this info is by looking back through your inbox on actors access. You’ll be able to quickly see who called you in for past self tapes!

2. According to the industry professionals I know… you don’t need a website anymore.  If you want one, keep it simple. Don’t teach yourself html *ahem, college Scarlet.* Your time and energy is better spent on your casting profiles, IMDb and creating at least a basic social media presence.

3. I used to edit reels! For money sometimes! I loved it. And UGHHH there is no sweeter feeling than the beauty of a perfectly cut montage to a kickass song. It’s extra tempting when you have a bunch of good looking footage with crappy sound. 

But montages have become notorious for the wrong reasons. They waste casting’s precious time as they try to scrub past them to the good stuff…aka: scenes of you acting. And that means they’re a waste of your time to edit. If you absolutely can’t bear to lose your heart swelling student film montage, I empathize! Just please put it at the END of your reel, babes!

The auditions FOR the audition. 

When people ask me how I handle all the rejection of being an actor, I never really know how to respond. I don’t feel the weight of my “rejections” all that much because I know how many times I had to BOOK something and get a resounding “yes!” just for the chance to audition for mainstream film, TV and commercial jobs.

My first #selftapemay is done! 16 tapes in 31 days! Audrey Moore’s @audreyhelpsactorspodcast was one of the first podcasts I ever listened to, and when she announced this annual challenge five years ago, I told myself I’d do it…someday. And I finally did. I feel like I cheated a little because ten of these were real auditions, but I guess that’s a well-known phenomenon with this challenge! It’s almost like the universe listens to you when you set a creative intention 🤔✨ 

I’m grateful to my reps for getting me seen for so many fun and challenging projects this month. And I’m super grateful to my readers! AND everyone who cheered me on in my DM’s! I wasn’t sure I’d get it done, the clock was running out. Sorry for spamming these in my stories constantly! But I wanted to create a highlight reel to organize them. Good luck to all my fellow tapers, can’t wait to see who wins the big fancy grand prize! 🤩 #selftapemay2023

🌙 Tonight, under the new moon, we begin something that is the OPPOSITE of new! “Hair” is back by popular demand @altadenamusictheatre and I’m counting my lucky, lucky stars that I get the very rare chance to revisit and expand on a role I loved playing. 

The cast, crew and band have almost all returned. We have the same, beautiful outdoor venue. This vital 55-year-old show is the same. But, in the 12 months since we did it the first time, the message has grown louder in our hearts. The friendships have deepened. The spirit of “Hair” has found its way into my life (as I was told it would!) I’ve never been part of anything quite like it and I really hope you can come witness the magic we’ve been making. 

If you saw it last year, I promise there *are* so many new elements you’ll love (new choreo, costumes, set design!) If you didn’t, please take advantage of this nearly unheard-of second chance. Ticket link in my bio or buy at the door! 🌙

Last week, I was driving down a dark, curvy highway in West Virginia when an orange kitten almost ran out in front of me. He was sitting with his little white paws on the asphalt as semi trucks tore by him. I knew what I had to do and I knew I had to do it FAST. I turned around at the next dirt path and parked at an abandoned gas station near where I’d seen him. “I’ll never find this kitten” I thought. “What if I find him and then scare him back out onto the highway?!” But then a new thought appeared “I can get him. I know I can.”

I found him sitting calmly on the old gas station steps. He looked sick and his meows sounded so hoarse. He rolled on his back and showed me his belly…he wanted to go with me. It only took a few minutes to coax him chose enough to grab him. I held him tight and got him in the car where he instantly curled up and started to purr 🥹 I knocked on doors, posted on social media, called the humane society and got him checked for a microchip…twice. No luck. So I named him Esso (after the old Esso gas stations and their orange tiger mascot!) and this week we flew back to LA.

There are so few moments in this world when we actually get to feel like we’ve made a measurable difference. When we know our love has tipped the scales. I found a little soul in need, I scooped him up and now I get to see him grow and play and thrive! After a few tough years of just trying to survive storm after storm, I’ve been struggling to feel powerful. I’ve been scared. At some point, I forgot how to trust my gut. How to fully go after things I want. I even had a litter box waiting for me back in LA because I’d been hoping to foster a kitten this summer, but I kept putting it off because it wasn’t the “right time.”

But the right time is always now! I’m so grateful for the people - and animals- in my life who’ve been encouraging me to go big lately. To remember who I am. To chase big dreams, big experiences, big love and big risk. To ask the universe for the life I want. And to never ever settle for less. Maybe connecting all of this to a kitten rescue only makes sense in my head, but that’s okay! 😻

TLDR: Karma is a cat, purring in my lap cause he loves me.

🪩 Here are my prettiest 2023 moments with some of the sweetest souls! I don’t have pictures of the many times I cried on my couch, abandoned one morning routine after another, or binged the same shows until my brain turned to soup. But that was ALSO my year. 

2023 was an important one. At some point this year, I feel like the last patches of grief fog I’d been wandering around in finally lifted. And once I stepped out, things looked (painfully) clear. In that post-pandemic/parent loss/work-place trauma fog I’d been stumbling through, I prioritized people and things that made me feel comforted. I’m sure lots of us did! But comfort isn’t comfortable after a while. It’s claustrophobic. I’m ready to get uncomfortable next year. To keep growing up and waking up. I have so many ideas for this next chapter…it’s semi-overwhelming! And for that, after a few years of feeling lost in that fog, I’m SO grateful. I feel like I’ve gotten Scarlet back. I love her spirit. And I really, really missed her.
✨ Coach Scarlet, at your service! Booking link in my bio, more info and client reviews can be found under the coaching tab at scarletsheppard.com …let’s go 2024! ✨
